The DPV responses for synthetic target nucleotides at different concentrations were recorded in 1 mL of 0.1 M PBS (pH 7.0). From Fig. 6a we can observe that the reduction peak current increases with increasing concentration of the target ssDNA solutions. The enhanced electrical conductivity of CDs/ZnO/PANI modified electrode, imparted by the ZnO nanorod and CDs to PANI matrix was found to be susceptible even for a lower concentration of ssDNA, which affects the in-turn increases the reduction peak current. Compared with other previously reported methods for the detection of E. coli, it is clear that the CDs/ZnO/PANI modified electrode has significantly improved the sensitivity with the lowest detection limit of 1.3 × 10−18M for E. coli. The calibration curves in Fig. 6b show a linear relationship from 1.3 × 10−18M to 5.2 × 10−12Mbetween the reduction peak current and the concentration of the target ssDNA.Detection limit of our method was the lowest one and linear range of our method was good. We have compared lowest detection limit of pathogens using different electrode materials and presented in Table 1
                        . As observed from Table 1, the present method produced significant result towards the detection E. coli. Further, the ZnO/CDs/PANI modified electrode based electrochemical DPV sensor was validated with other pathogens like Vibrio cholerae, Cryptosporidium parvum and Salmonella, and it was found that the ZnO/CDs/PANI modified electrode was highly specific to E. coli and no false positive or non-specific binding of ssDNA were detected, interms of DPV reduction peak current (Fig. 7
                        ).
